      "content": "The most common mistake is actually being too loose, often called \"privilege creep,\" where employees gradually accumulate unnecessary access rights over time as they transfer files or get invited to different teams. This happens because humans are naturally lazy and prefer the ease of having a \"master key\" to the entire system rather than the tedious process of requesting specific permissions for every new task. In contrast, being too strict can lead to workflow bottlenecks where legitimate users are locked out of necessary tools, causing frustration and potentially forcing admins to manually grant exceptions that bypass security controls.\n\nTo avoid these pitfalls, you need to maintain a strict \"access review\" process where permissions are audited quarterly and any access not actively used is immediately revoked. It is also crucial to remember that every new piece of software or script you install should be treated as a potential entry point for an attacker, requiring the creator to apply the Principle of Least Privilege from day one. If you let the system get too complex, you risk creating a \"goblin\" scenario where the security measures become so tangled that they effectively grant everyone a master key just to keep things running.",
